claims:
1. A method of manufacturing a high strength ferritic/martensitic steel, the method comprising:
melting a ferritic/martensitic steel;
hot-working the melted ferritic/martensitic steel;
normalizing the hot-worked ferritic/martensitic steel at a temperature of about 1050° C. to about 1200° C.;
tempering the normalized ferritic/martensitic steel; and
cold-working the tempered ferritic/martensitic steel in a multistage fashion, and thermal-treating the cold-worked ferritic/martensitic steel in a multistage fashion at a temperature of about 730° C. to 780° C. to correspond to the cold-working in the multistage fashion.
2. The method of claim 1, wherein the tempering includes thermal-treating the normalized ferritic/martensitic steel at a temperature of about 600° C. or less.
3. The method of claim 2, wherein the thermal-treated ferritic/martensitic steel obtained by thermal-treating the normalized ferritic/martensitic steel is cold-worked by about 95% by the cold-working and the thermal-treating performed in the multistage fashion.
4. The method of claim 3, wherein the cold-working and the thermal-treating includes cold-working the ferritic/martensitic steel in three stages or more, and a cold-working ratio of each stage is about 5% to 95%.
5. The method of claim 4, wherein the cold-working and the thermal-treating includes cold-working the ferritic/martensitic steel while maintaining an atmosphere of a temperature of about 730° C. to about 780° C. for 1 to 30 minutes to thereby precipitate a M<sub>23</sub>C<sub>6 </sub>precipitate, when the cold-working of each stage is completed.
6. A method of manufacturing a high strength ferritic/martensitic steel, the method comprising:
melting a ferritic/martensitic steel;
hot-working the melted ferritic/martensitic steel;
normalizing the hot-worked ferritic/martensitic steel at a temperature of about 1050° C. to about 1200° C.;
tempering the ferritic/martensitic steel, and leaving MX precipitates while avoiding the formation of M<sub>23</sub>C<sub>6 </sub>precipitates; and
cold-working and thermal-treating the ferritic/martensitic steel in a multistage fashion, and precipitating M<sub>23</sub>C<sub>6 </sub>precipitates.
7. The method of claim 6, wherein the leaving of the MX precipitates while avoiding the formation of M<sub>23</sub>C<sub>6 </sub>precipitates is performed by heating the ferritic/martensitic steel to a temperature of about 600° C. or less.
8. The method of claim 6, wherein the precipitating of the M<sub>23</sub>C<sub>6 </sub>precipitate repeatedly performs the thermal-treating at a temperature of about 730° C. to about 780° C. at least three times after cold-working the ferritic/martensitic steel.
